Sales Forecast with Winter-Holts Method

Iryna G Duda

  • Since the time when pandemic started, department’s sales appear to be unpredictable. Thus, to better understand the direction of department performance, it makes sense first to explore the sales during the pre-pandemic normal times and find the prior associations.
    So the purpose of this analysis is to predict sales based on the time series using historical data from 2016 to pre-pandemic period (February, 2020). Further compare predicted values with the actual data and make the determination how applicable Winter-Holts model can be.

3. Evaluating ACF and PACF plots

ACF plot shows the significant correlation between current time series and previous lags. Typically, such assumption is appropriate when time series, represented by vertical lines, cross the level of significance (blue dashed line) just as it appears in this case. Also, observation suggests presence of correlation between the last 3 terms, which makes the lag possibly equal to 3. Since time series drop gradually, there is an assumption of non-stationary data behavior. In case of a sudden drop it would point on the stationary data and zero correlation between lags.

PACF also suggests lag equal to 3, because of the first three vertical lines, that are above the 95% of significance level.
To verify above assumptions, adf.test() is performed. Null hypothesis states that data is non-stationary. Thus p-value is 0.144 which is more then excepted 0.05, we fail to reject null hypothesis and have enough evidence to assume that the data is non-stationary. Adf.test() also recommends lag of 3, which confirms findings from the plots.

par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
# Modeling time series against Invoice Values per plots ACF
# and PACF
acf(as.ts(dataset[13:50, ]$TotalInv), main = "Sales")  #excluded years 2020 [52:54,] and 2016
pacf(as.ts(dataset[13:50, ]$TotalInv), main = "Sales")

par(mfrow = c(1, 1))

tseries::adf.test(TotalInv[13:50], alternative = "stationary")
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  TotalInv[13:50]
## Dickey-Fuller = -3.0986, Lag order = 3, p-value =
## 0.144
## alternative hypothesis: stationary

4. Considering Exponential Smoothening with Additive and Multiplicative types

Plot of monthly sales growth shows trend of increase. Thus, need to look at the decomposed data to analyze seasonal behavior.

ts_hw <- ts(TotalInv[13:50], frequency = 12, start = c(2017, 
    1))
dataset_ts <- window(ts_hw, start = c(2017, 1), end = c(2019, 
    10))
autoplot(dataset_ts) + ylab("Year") + xlab("Monthly Sales")

decompos_add <- decompose(dataset_ts, type = "additive")
decompos_mult <- decompose(dataset_ts, type = "mult")

5. Using the Winter-Holts method to predict sales

Side by side forecasts for both “additive” and “multiplicative” model types are demonstrated below.

fit1 <- hw(dataset_ts, seasonal = "additive")
fit2 <- hw(dataset_ts, seasonal = "multiplicative")
autoplot(dataset_ts) + autolayer(fit1, series = "HW additive forecast", 
    PI = FALSE) + autolayer(fit2, series = "HW multiplicative forecast", 
    PI = FALSE)

Earlier decomposed plots showed an increase in trend and steady seasonality. This suggests that appropriate seasonal type would be an “additive”. Thus, the fitted values (red line) and forecast values (blue line) are compared to the actual values (black line).

plot(forecast(fit1, 12))

lines(fitted(fit1), col = "red")
lines(ts_hw, col = "black")

actuals <- filter(dataset0, dataset0$Yr > 2019)
actuals <- actuals[, c(1, 2, 3, 9)]
actuals <- actuals[order(actuals$Mo_No, decreasing = TRUE), ]
actuals
comp <- cbind(yr = actuals$Yr, month = order(actuals$Mo_No, decreasing = TRUE), 
    predicted = f$mean[3:9], actuals = actuals$TotalInv, error_per = (f$mean[3:9] - 
        actuals$TotalInv)/actuals$TotalInv * 100)

Comparison below show the the underestimation of the predicted sales for January and February of 2020 (pre-pandemic months) and overestimation after 2 months into pandemic time (June and July), which is expected.
While actual sales show fast recovery, there is an exciting anticipation when actual will meet predicted sales and align themselves with the pre-pandemic forecast.
